Group A: Short Questions (2 Marks)
# Define Information Architecture (IA).
Information Architecture (IA) is the practice of organizing, structuring, and labeling content on a website so users can easily find and understand information.

 # what is a “Wireframe”?
 - A wireframe is a basic visual blueprint of a webpage that shows layout, content placement, and functionality without design details like colors or images.

# Explain the concept of “Cognitive Friction” in web design.
-Cognitive friction refers to the mental effort required by users when a website is confusing, cluttered, or inconsistent, making tasks harder to complete.

#Why should URL slugs use hyphens instead of underscores?
-Search engines treat ,hyphens (-) as word separators
Underscores (_) are read as one word
#Example:
 web-design basics (readable)
- web design basics (less SEO-friendly)

Group B: Long Questions 
 Compare Hierarchical  structure and Linear (Sequential) structure.
-Aspect Hierarchical Structure	Linear Structure
 Organization	Parent–child relationship	Step-by-step order
 Navigation	Multiple paths	Single path
 Best Large, complex websites	Tutorials, forms

Examples:
Hierarchical: University website (Departments → Courses)
Linear: Online exam or checkout process

 Explain the “Three-Click Rule” and its significance in UX design.
-The Three-Click Rule suggests users should find information within three clicks.
-Significance:
Reduces frustration
Improves engagement
Encourages better navigation 

# “Plan before you do” Explain how Card Sorting and Flowcharts help.
Card Sorting: Helps understand how users naturally group content

Flowcharts: Show user paths and page relationships

Together, they:

Improve navigation logic

Reduce confusion

Save redesign time

Group C: Scenario-Based Questions (5 Marks)
8. University Website Structure

Chosen Model: Hierarchical (Tree) Structure

Justification:

Handles large content efficiently

Matches user mental models

Allows easy expansion

Rough Diagram:

Home
 ├── Admissions
 │    ├── UG
 │    └── PG
 ├── Departments
 │    ├── Science
 │    └── Arts
 ├── Alumni
 └── News

9. Navigation Failure & KISS Principle Analysis

Problem:

Navigation hidden behind a small icon on desktop

Users cannot find it quickly

KISS Principle Violation:

Desktop users expect visible menus

Over-minimalism increases confusion

Result:

High bounce rate

Poor usability

Solution:

Use clear, visible navigation

Avoid hiding essential elements unnecessarily

10. Bad URL Structure Analysis & Improved SEO-Friendly Version

Bad URL:

www.shop.com/prod?id=55&cat=9

Why it’s bad:

Not readable by humans

Hard to remember or share

Poor SEO (no keywords)

Search engines can’t infer page meaning

Better URL using Page Slugs:
www.shop.com/electronics/smartphone


Benefits:

User-friendly

Keyword-rich

Improves SEO ranking

Clearly describes content
